===Council for Aid to Education=== The Council for Aid to Education publishes a list of the top universities in terms of annual fundraising. Fundraising ability reflects, among other things, alumni and outside donor's views of the quality of a university, as well as the ability of that university to expend funds on top faculty and facilities. Most recent 2017 rankings put Harvard at the top, ahead of Stanford and Cornell.<ref>{{cite web|title = Top Fundraisers|url = http://cae.org/images/uploads/pdf/VSE_2017_Press_Release.pdf|accessdate = 26 March 2018}}{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Notable among universities without medical schools are [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|MIT]], [[University of Notre Dame|Notre Dame]], and [[University of California, Berkeley|Berkeley]], while [[University of California, San Francisco|UCSF]] is a research university offering only post-baccalaureate programs in medicine and the health sciences. {| class="wikitable sortable" !University ! data-sort-type="number" |2017 Fundraising Total in $Millions |- |- |align="center" |[[Harvard University]] |align="center" |1,280 |- |align="center" |[[Stanford University]] |align="center" |1,130 |- |align="center" |[[Cornell University]] |align="center" |743.50 |- |align="center" |[[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] |align="center" |672.94 |- |align="center" |[[University of Southern California]] |align="center" |668.33 |- |align="center" |[[Johns Hopkins University]] |align="center" |636.91 |- |align="center" |[[University of Pennsylvania]] |align="center" |626.49 |- |align="center" |[[Columbia University]] |align="center" |603.08 |- |align="center" |[[Yale University]] |align="center" |595.89 |- |align="center" |[[Duke University]] |align="center" |581.05 |- |align="center" |[[New York University]] |align="center" |567.12 |- |align="center" |[[University of Washington]] |align="center" |553.89 |- |align="center" |[[University of Calif