===Educate to Career rankings===
Educate to Career<ref>https://www.jobsearchintelligence.com/etc/college-rankings.php</ref> ranks school by improvement in earnings and employment in the labor market, based on percentage of students employed in occupations that use their field of study, weighted against national norms.<ref>http://blogs.edweek.org/edweek/college_bound/2014/07/college_ranking_to_show_economic_value.html</ref>
===Faculty Scholarly Productivity rankings=== The [[Faculty Scholarly Productivity Index]] by Academic Analytics ranks 354 institutions based on faculty publications, citations, research grants and awards.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.academicanalytics.com/ | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080822232018/http://www.academicanalytics.com/TopSchools/TopSchools.aspx | title=FSP Index Top Performing Schools | date=2008-08-22 | archivedate=2008-08-22 | publisher=Academic Analytics, LLC | accessdate=2009-09-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://president.arizona.edu/highlight_ranking/324 | title=The Faculty Scholarly Productivity Index, a means of assessing doctoral programs | publisher=Office of the President | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101010061257/http://president.arizona.edu/highlight_ranking/324 | archivedate=2010-10-10 | df= }}</ref>
===''Forbes'' college rankings=== In 2008, [[Forbes|Forbes.com]] began publishing an annual list of "America's Best Colleges".<ref>{{cite web|title = America's Top Colleges|publisher = Forbes|url = https://www.forbes.com/top-colleges/|accessdate = 29 October 2011}}</ref> '''Post-graduate success''' (self-reported salaries of alumni from [[PayScale]], and data from the [[United States Department of Education|Department of Education]]) constitutes 35% of the score. '''Student debt loads''' constitute 20% of the score. '''Student experience''' ([[retention rate]]s reported by the Department of Education, and data from [[Niche (company)|Niche]]) constitutes 20% of the score. '''Graduation rates''' constitute 12.5% of the score. '''Academic success''' (using both the percentage of a school's student body that goes on to obtain doctorate degrees, and those students who have won one of a diverse array of prestigious academic awards) constitutes 12.5%. Public [[reputation]] is not considered, which causes some colleges to score lower than in other lists. A three-year [[moving average]] is used to smooth out the scoring. The 2018 ranking puts Harvard University at the top, followed by Yale University, Stanford University, the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, and Princeton University. {| class="wikitable sortable" !University ! data-sort-type="number" |Top College Ranking |- |- |align="center" |[[Harvard University]] |align="center" |1 |- |align="center" |[[Yale University]] |align="center" |2 |- |align="center" |[[Stanford University]] |align="center" |3 |- |align="center" |[[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] |align="center" |4 |- |align="center" |[[Princeton University]] |align="center" |5 |- |align="center" |[[California Institute of Technology]] |align="center" |6 |- |align="center" |[[University of Pennsylvania]] |align="center" |7 |- |align="center" |[[Brown University]] |align="center" |8 |- |align="center" |[[Dartmouth College]] |align="center" |9 |- |align="center" |[[Duke University]] |align="center" |10 |- |align="center" |[[Williams College]] |align="center" |11 |- |align="center" |[[Georgetown University]] |align="center" |12 |- |align="center" |[[Cornell University]] |align="center" |13 |- |align="center" |[[University of California, Berkeley]] |align="center" |14 |- |align="center" |[[Columbia University]] |align="center" |15 |- |align="center" |[[Amherst College]] |align="center" |16 |- |align="center" |[[Bowdoin College]] |align="center" |17 |- |align="center" |[[University of Chicago]] |align="center" |18 |- |align="center" |[[Pomona College]] |align="center" |19 |- |align="center" |[[Northwestern University]] |align="center" |20 |} {{reflist|group=a}}
===Innovative universities=== [[Reuters]] ranks the most innovative universities in the world based upon its assessment of the educational institutions "doing the most to advance science, invent new technologies and power new markets and industries."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-amers-reuters-ranking-innovative-univ/reuters-top-100-the-worlds-most-innovative-universities-2017-idUSKCN1C209R |title=Reuters Top 100: The World's Most Innovative Universities - 2017 |accessdate=October 9, 2017}}</ref> The assessment evaluates 10 different metrics, "focusing on academic papers (which indicate basic research) and patent filings (which point to an institution’s ability to apply research and commercialize its discoveries)," and ranks them based on their performance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-amers-reuters-ranking-innovative-univ/reuters-top-100-the-worlds-most-innovative-universities-2017-idUSKCN1C209R |title=Reuters Top 100: The World's Most Innovative Universities - 2017 |accessdate=October 9, 2017}}</ref> For the third year in a row, Stanford University has topped the list as the most innovative university in the world, followed by MIT and Harvard in second and third place.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-amers-reuters-ranking-innovative-univ/reuters-top-100-the-worlds-most-innovative-universities-2017-idUSKCN1C209R |title=Reuters Top 100: The World's Most Innovative Universities - 2017 |accessdate=October 9, 2017}}</ref> {| class="wikitable sortable" |+Reuters: World's Most Innovative Universities (2017) !College ! data-sort-type="number" |College ranking |- |- |align="center" |[[Stanford University]] |align="center" |1 |- |align="center" |[[MIT]] |align="center" |2 |- |align="center" |[[Harvard University]] |align="center" |3 |- |align="center" |[[University of Pennsylvania]] |align="center" |4 |- |align="center" |[[KU Leuven]] |align="center" |5 |- |align="center" |[[KAIST]] |align="center" |6 |-