===''Money'''s "Best Colleges"=== ''[[Money (magazine)|Money]]'''s college rankings take into account 21 factors that it categorizes as measures of educational quality, affordability, and alumni earnings. The rankings considered 1500 four-year colleges and reported the top ranking 736. In 2017, according to Money, the top 5 colleges are Princeton, Baruch College, Michigan-Ann Arbor, Berkeley, and UCLA.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://best-colleges.time.com/money/full-ranking#/list |title=MONEY's Best Colleges |publisher=Time |accessdate=July 31, 2015}}</ref> {| class="wikitable sortable" !College ! data-sort-type="number" |College ranking |- |- |align="center" |[[Princeton University]] |align="center" |1 |- |align="center" |[[Baruch College]] |align="center" |2 |- |align="center" |[[University of Michigan]] |align="center" |3 |- |align="center" |[[University of California, Berkeley]] |align="center" |4 |- |align="center" |[[University of California, Los Angeles]] |align="center" |5 |- |align="center" |[[Stanford University]] |align="center" |6 |- |align="center" |[[University of California, Irvine]] |align="center" |7 |- |align="center" |[[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] |align="center" |8 |- |align="center" |[[University of California, Davis]] |align="center" |9 |- |align="center" |[[Harvard University]] |align="center" |10 |- |} {{reflist|group=a}}
===Niche rankings=== Niche provides rankings and reviews of colleges in the U.S. Their Best Colleges ranking focuses on academics, diversity, affordability, and student satisfaction. Their most recent ranking places Stanford at the top, followed by MIT, Yale, Harvard, and Rice University<ref>{{cite web|url=https://colleges.niche.com/rankings/best-colleges/ |title=Niche Best Colleges}}</ref> {| class="wikitable sortable" !University ! data-sort-type="number" |College Ranking |- |- |align="center" |[[Stanford University]] |align="center" |1 |- |align="center" |[[MIT]] |align="center" |2 |- |align="center" |[[Harvard University]] |align="center" |3 |- |align="center" |[[Yale University]] |align="center" |4 |- |align="center" |[[Rice University]] |align="center" |5 |- |align="center" |[[Princeton University]] |align="center" |6 |- |align="center" |[[University of Pennsylvania]] |align="center" |7 |- |align="center" |[[Brown University]] |align="center" |8 |- |align="center" |[[Bowdoin College]] |align="center" |9 |- |align="center" |[[Caltech]] |align="center" |10 |- |} {{reflist|group=a}}
===The Princeton Review Dream Colleges=== The Princeton Review annually asks students and parents what their dream college is, if cost and ability to get in were not factors. Over 10,000 students and parents responded in 2016. The top dream school for students is Stanford, for the fourth year in a row. The top dream school for parents is also Stanford, for the fifth year in a row. Stanford won out over Harvard and NYU among students, and led Harvard and Princeton among parents.<ref>{{cite web|title = Top 10 "Dream Colleges" |url = http://www.princetonreview.com/press/college-hopes-worries-press-release|accessdate = 8 May 2016}}</ref> {| class="wikitable sortable" !University ! data-sort-type="number" |Students' Dream <br> College Ranking |- |- |align="center" |[[Stanford University|Stanford]] |align="center" |1 |- |align="center" |[[Harvard College|Harvard]] |align="center" |2 |- |align="center" |[[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|MIT]] |align="center" |3 |- |align="center" |[[New York University|NYU]] |align="center" |4 |- |align="center" |[[University of California, Los Angeles|UCLA]] |align="center" |5 |- |align="center" |[[Columbia University|Columbia]] |align="center" |6 |- |align="center" |[[Princeton University|Princeton]] |align="center" |7 |- |align="center" |[[University of California, Berkeley|Berkeley]] |align="center" |8 |- |align="center" |[[University of Pennsylvania|Pennsylvania]] |align="center" |9 |- |align="center" |[[Yale University|Yale]] |align="center" |10 |} {{reflist|group=a}} {| class="wikitable sortable" !University ! data-sort-type="number" |Parents' Dream <br> College Ranking |- |- |align="center" |[[Stanford University]] |align="center" |1 |- |align="center" |[[Princeton University]] |align="center" |2 |- |align="center" |[[Harvard College]] |align="center" |3 |- |align="center" |[[MIT]] |align="center" |4 |- |align="center" |[[Duke University]] |align="center" |5 |} {{reflist|group=a}}
===Revealed Preference Rankings=== Avery ''et al.'' pioneered the use of [[choice modelling]] to rank colleges. Their methodology used a statistical analysis of the decisions of 3,240 students who applied to college in 1999.<ref>{{cite journal |ssrn=601105 |title=A Revealed Preference Ranking of U.S. Colleges and Universities |work= }}</ref> MyChances.net adopted a similar approach starting in 2009,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://college.mychances.net/college-rankings.php?thisYear=2009&thisCategory=National |title=2009–2010 College Rankings: National Universities |format= |work= |accessdate=2010-07-17}}</ref> stating that its method is based on this approach.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mychances.net/blog/2009/07/10/new-college-rankings/ |title=New College Rankings |format= |work= |accessdate=2010-07-17}}</ref> The study analysed students admitted to multiple colleges. The college they attended became the winner, and the others became the losers. An [[Elo rating system]] was used to assign points based on each win or loss, and the colleges were ranked based on their Elo points. A useful consequence of the use of Elo points is that they can be used to estimate the frequency with which students, upon being admitted to two schools, will choose one over the other. The most recent preference ranking by Parchment placed MIT at the top, followed by Williams, Stanford, US Air Force Academy, and Claremont McKenna College.<ref>{{cite web |title=Parchment Rankings |url=http://www.parchment.com/c/college/college-rankings.php}}</ref> {| class="wikitable sortable" !University ! data-sort-type="number" |Total Points |- |- |align="center" |[[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] |align="center" |2239 |- |align="center" |[[Williams College]] |align="center" |2161 |- |align="center" |[[Stanford University]] |align="center" |2131 |- |align="center" |[[United States Air Force Academy]] |align="center" |2116 |- |align="center" |[[Claremont McKenna College]] |align="center" |2107 |- |align="center" |[[United States Military Academy]] |align="center" |2104 |- |align="center" |[[Columbia University]] |align="center" |2096 |- |align="center" |[[Bowdoin College]] |align="center" |2095 |- |align="center" |[[United States Merchant Marine Academy]] |align="center" |2095 |- |align="center" |[[Yale University]] |align="center" |2077 |} {{reflist|group=a}}
===Social Mobility Index (SMI) rankings=== The SMI rankings are a collaborative publication from CollegeNet and PayScale. The rankings aim to provide a measure of the extent to which colleges provide upward economic mobility to those that attend. The rankings were created in response to the finding in Science magazine which showed that among developed nations, the United States now provides the least economic opportunity and mobility for its citizens. The rankings were also created to combat the rising costs of tuition, much of which is attributed to the efforts of some colleges to increase their own fame and wealth in ways that increase their rank in media periodicals that put an emphasis on such measures. In 2014, according to the SMI, the top five colleges are Montana Tech, Rowan University, Florida A&M, Cal Poly Pomona, and Cal State Northridge.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://socialmobilityindex.org/ |title=Social Mobility Index |publisher=CollegeNet and Payscale |accessdate=October 21, 2014}}</ref>
===The Top American Research Universities=== [[Center for Measuring University Performance|The Center for Measuring University Performance]] has ranked American research universities in the Top American Research Universities since 2000. The methodology is based on data such as research publications, citations, recognitions and funding, as well as undergraduate quality such as SAT scores. The information used can be found in publicly accessible materials, reducing possibilities for manipulation. The methodology is generally consistent from year to year and changes are explained in the publication along with references from other studies.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://mup.asu.edu/research.html | title=The Top American Research Universities | publisher=The Center for Measuring University Performance | accessdate=2009-08-23 | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120617210050/http://mup.asu.edu/research.html | archivedate=2012-06-17 | df= }}</ref>
===TrendTopper MediaBuzz College Guide=== [[TrendTopper MediaBuzz College Guide]] is an American-college guide based on what it calls "Internet brand equity" based on data collected from the Internet and global media sources. It ranks the Top 300 United States colleges and universities. The guide includes specialty and for profit schools including Art, Business, Design, Music, and Online Education. The TrendTopper MediaBuzz College Rankings are produced twice a year by the [[Global Language Monitor]] of [[Austin]], [[Texas]].{{citation needed|date=September 2014}}
[[Time Magazine]] described internet brand equity as "a measure of who's talking about you online, based on Internet data, social media, blogs and the top 75,000 print and electronic media outlets.<ref>[http://newsfeed.time.com/2011/01/05/the-most-buzzed-about-university-wisconsin/ The Most Buzzed-About University?]</ref><ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/2010/12/30/us-universities-topbrands-idUSTRE6BT41J20101230/ Harvard, Yale Beaten]</ref>
GLM ranks the schools "according to their online presence -- or internet brand equity ... By focusing on online presence, the Monitor hopes to avoid the biases that characterize other rankings, which commonly rely on the opinions of university officials and college counselors rather than that of the greater public.<ref>[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/01/10/buzzworthy-schools-which-_n_806809.html#s221586&title=University_of_WisconsinMadison/ The Most Buzz Worthy Schools]</ref>" GLM believes the rankings provide an up-to-date perspective on which schools have the most popular brand. The resulting rankings gauge the relative value of the various institutions and how they change over time.
The Global Language Monitor publishes other lists relating to the English language including: the [[TrendTopper MediaBuzz College Guide]] rankings of the top 425 U.S. colleges and universities according to their internet [[brand equity]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.languagemonitor.com/category/top-colleges/# |title=Trendtopper MediaBuzz 2016 University Rankings |access-date=2016-03-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140811175548/http://www.languagemonitor.com/category/top-colleges/# |archive-date=2014-08-11 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref>
