'''Rex Ziak''' (pronounced "zeek") is a [[writer]], [[historian]], [[tour guide]], and [[documentarian]], who lives in [[Naselle, Washington]], United States. Known for his [[Lewis and Clark Expedition|Lewis and Clark]] studies, he is the author of ''In Full View.''<ref>{{cite news |title=His colorful past helps author track Lewis and Clark |author=Dean Baker |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-23219983.html |newspaper=[[The Columbian]] |date=December 6, 2002 |accessdate=April 27, 2012|subscription=yes}}</ref> After careful study of the expedition's journals and of the geography of the [[Columbia River]] [[estuary]], Ziak discovered the previously unknown fact that from November 7, 1805 to December 6, the Lewis and Clark expedition stayed in what is now [[Pacific County]], along the [[Long Beach Peninsula]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Long Beach is discovering its historic place along the Lewis and Clark trail |author=Jon Hahn |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-92558776.html |newspaper=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]] |date=August 30, 2001 |accessdate=April 27, 2012|subscription=yes}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=On the money trail 200 years later hoping to reap benefits, Long Beach peninsula plays up ties to Lewis and Clark |author=Claudia Rowe |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-112866543.html |newspaper=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]] |date=February 2, 2004 |accessdate=April 27, 2012|subscription=yes}}</ref> This finding took six years for Ziak to piece together, using the comments in the expedition's journals to find the locations the explorers stopped at on their trip. A controversy arose between Oregon, long considered the end of the expedition, and Washington's historians over Ziak's findings, with many historians in Washington and elsewhere supporting his discovery and many in Oregon opposing it.<ref>{{cite news |title=Controversy blurs path of Lewis, Clark |author=Thomas W. Haines |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-8524385.html |newspaper=[[The Boston Globe]] |date=February 22, 1999 |accessdate=April 27, 2012|subscription=yes}}</ref> In 1999, soon after his announcement, Ziak and David Nicandri, director of the Washington State Historical Society, began petitioning to give the newly found ending location, a camping spot called Station Camp, National Landmark Status. In addition, that year, [[United States House of Representatives|US Representative]] [[Brian Baird]] had an amendment passed that changed the "federal designation of the Lewis and CLark National Historic Trail as ending not in Oregon but in Oregon and Washington."<ref>{{cite news |title=Dollars, pride at stake in Lewis and Clark history debate |author=[[Staff writer]] |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=HgEgAAAAIBAJ&sjid=lhMFAAAAIBAJ&pg=6291,4642322&dq=rex-ziak&hl=en |newspaper=[[Associated Press]] |date=March 15, 2000 |accessdate=April 27, 2012|subscription=yes}}</ref>
In 2004, Ziak testified before Congress in support of the [[Lewis and Clark National and State Historical Parks]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Parks Bills:Rex Ziak |author= |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-94926086.html |newspaper=Federal Document Clearing House |date=May 20, 2004 |accessdate=April 27, 2012|subscription=yes}}</ref> The next year he published a fold-out map and guide to the route taken by the expedition.<ref>''Lewis and Clark: Down and Up the Columbia River'' (Moffitt House Press, 2005)</ref>
As a documentarian and cinematographer, his work under assignment from [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC Television]] received an [[Emmy Award|Emmy]] in 1993 for cinematography in the documentary ''Tall Ship: High Sea Adventure''. He was also involved in the filming of the 2003 [[Discovery Channel]] documentary, ''Marine Corps Survival School'', where Ziak had to film at "high altitudes and in low temperatures" in the [[Sierra Nevada (U.S.)|Sierra Nevada]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Rex on ice: Local cinematographer's latest adventure airs Friday |author=Nancy Butterfield |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=CKOR&p_multi=CKOB&p_theme=ckor&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=11620D132D4C40A0&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |newspaper=Chinook Observer |date=November 6, 2002 |accessdate=April 27, 2012|subscription=yes}}</ref> As a local activist and regional historian, he has served as a consultant to the City of [[Long Beach, Washington|Long Beach]] and as a board member of the Pacific County Friends of Lewis and Clark. Ziak has also run unsuccessfully for local political office.{{citation needed|date=April 2012}}
==Bibliography== * ''In Full View (A True and Accurate Account of Lewis and Clark's Arrival at the Pacific Ocean, and Their Search for a Winter Camp Along the Lower Columbia River)'' (Moffitt House Press, 2002)
